[[File:Antun Barac Ck 290708.jpg|thumb|upright|A monument to Antun Barac in [[Crikvenica]]]]
'''Antun Barac''' ([[Kamenjak]], 20 August 1894&nbsp;– [[Zagreb]], 1 November 1955), was a [[Croats|Croatian]] historian.

==Biography==
Barac graduated at the [[Faculty of Humanities and Social Sciences, University of Zagreb|Faculty of philosophy]] at the [[University of Zagreb]] in 1917, and received his Ph.D. as a high school professor on [[Sušak, Rijeka|Sušak]] in 1918, with the thesis on [[Vladimir Nazor]]'s poetry. Since 1930 he is a regular professor at the Faculty of Philosophy in Zagreb. He was accepted as a regular member of [[JAZU]] in 1947.

He edited numerous scientific editions and anthologies, and has written high school handbooks together with Nazor. He served as a prorector of the University of Zagreb after his rectorship mandate expired (1950–1951). He was a significant contributor to modern Croatian [[literary theory]], especially in the position of [[Croatian literature]] in the European context. He published numerous monographies on top Croatian artists such as [[Vladimir Nazor|Nazor]], [[August Šenoa|Šenoa]], [[Vladimir Vidrić|Vidrić]] or [[Ivan Mažuranić|Mažuranić]], a number of critic-essayist writings on lesser known writers, as well as great syntheses on Croatian literary criticism of the 19th century, and the unfinished history of Croatian literature from [[Croatian National Revival]] to the time of creation of [[Yugoslavia]].

A square in [[Novi Zagreb]] is named after him.

==Literary criticism==
Barac's valorisation of literature is based on the two tenets: the literature has to be an expression of a man in his totality, as an individual and social being, deeply covering the basic aspects of life. His other tenet is that the great art is born only out of the great pain.

His studies were permeated by a specific national criterion, holding that every little literature to a more or less extent reflects the social life of its people, as opposed to the large national literature. This view is reflected in his well-known maxim on the greatness of the small.

