'''Louis C. Hunter''' (1898 – 1984) was a [[professor]] of [[economic history]] at [[American University]]. His most famous work, ''Steamboats on the Western Rivers, an Economic and Technological History'', was published in 1949.<ref name="Hunter (1949)">Hunter, Louis C. (1949). ''Steamboats on the western rivers, an economic and technological history''. Cambridge: Harvard University Press</ref>
Hunter grew up in a [[steamboat]] [[culture]] as he spent his first eighteen years living on the banks of the [[Ohio River]], at [[Wellsburg, West Virginia]], and the [[Mississippi River]], at [[Moline, Illinois]].<ref name=White>White, John H. (1993). "Introduction to the Dover edition", ''Steamboats on the western rivers, an economic and technological history''. Mineola, New York: Dover Publications. A biography of Louis C. Hunter by John H. White, Senior Historian Emeritus of the [[Smithsonian Institution]].</ref> After studying [[engineering]] and [[economic history]] at [[Harvard University]], he received a [[doctorate]] in 1928.<ref name=White/> For the next twenty years, Hunter was engaged in research for ''Steamboats on the Western Rivers''.<ref name=White/> In 1952, his scholarship was acknowledged when he was awarded the [[John H. Dunning Prize|Dunning Prize]] by the [[American Historical Association]].<ref name=White/>
In 1937, Hunter joined the faculty of American University where he was a professor of history until his retirement in 1966.<ref name=White/><ref name=nytobit>{{cite news|last=Waggoner|first=Walter|title=LOUIS C. HUNTER IS DEAD; A SPECIALIST ON U.S. INDUSTRY|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/03/24/obituaries/louis-c-hunter-is-dead-a-specialist-on-us-industry.html|accessdate=2 July 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=24 March 1984}}</ref> In 1979, the first volume of his trilogy, ''A History of Industrial Power in the United States, 1780-1930'', was published.<ref name=White/> In 1983, Dr. Hunter was awarded the [[Leonardo da Vinci Medal]] by the Society of History of Technology.<ref name=White/>
Hunter was married and the father of two daughters.<ref name=White/> Louis C. Hunter died on March 22, 1984.<ref name=White/>
