{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}} {{Infobox person |name = Simon J.J. Corcoran |image = Simon Corcoran 2003.jpg |caption = Simon Corcoran in 2003, [[Knap of Howar]] |known_for = Roman Law |alma_mater = [[St John's College, Oxford]] |employer = [[Newcastle University]] |occupation = Historian |website = http://www.roman-empire.co.uk }}
'''Simon Corcoran''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|k|ɔr|k|ər|ən}}) is a British [[ancient history|ancient historian]] and lecturer in ancient history within the School of History, Classics and Archaeology, [[Newcastle University]].<ref name=ncl>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncl.ac.uk/hca/staff/profile/simoncorcoran.html |title=Staff Profile - History, Classics and Archaeology, School of - Newcastle University |publisher=Ncl.ac.uk |date=2016-11-08 |accessdate=2016-11-13}}</ref>
Corcoran was a senior research fellow at [[University College, London]] from 1999 to 2015. He received his D.Phil. from [[St John's College, Oxford]] in 1992. He was awarded the [[:pl:Henryk Kupiszewski|Henryk Kupiszewski]] Prize<ref>{{citation|url=http://www2.ulg.ac.be/vinitor/rida/1998/BOULVERT.pdf|title=Relazione della Commissione giudicatrice del "Quarto premio romanistico internazionale Gérard Boulvert"|year=1998|quote=Il Premio del Centro Romanistico Internazionale “Copanello”, intitolato ad Henryk KUPISZEWSKI e destinato a contribuire alla maggior diffusione del diritto romano, al volume di Simon Corcoran, The Empire of the Tetrarchs, ... avendo formulato su di essa il seguente giudizio: “Importante opera sulla produzione normativa dell'età dioclezianea, che si fa apprezzare per il sapiente uso delle fonti e la chiarezza dell'esposizione”|language=Italian}}</ref> for his book ''The Empire of the Tetrarchs'' in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/history/People/Academic_Staff/corcoran|title=Staff page at UCL|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090419171941/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/history/People/Academic_Staff/corcoran|archivedate=2009-04-19}}</ref> At University College he worked on 'Projet Volterra',<ref>{{citation |title=Project Volterra |oclc=44255728 |url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/history2/volterra/ |quote=Presents Project Volterra, one of the Research Projects of the British Academy that is based in the History Department of University College London. Explains that the aim of the project is to promote the study of Roman legislation in its full social, political, and legal context. |publisher=[[University College London]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5uESqJ7K2?url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/history2/volterra/ |archivedate=14 November 2010 |deadurl=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref> an extensive on-line public database of law ([[Roman law|Roman]], [[Germanic law|Germanic]] or ‘barbarian’, and [[ecclesiastical law|ecclesiastical]]) for the period AD193–900.
From 2014 Corcoran has been a member of the Steering Committee of the [[British Epigraphy Society]].<ref name=ncl/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishepigraphysociety.org/steering-committee.html/ |title=Steering Committee |publisher=The British Epigraphy Society |date= |accessdate=2016-11-13}}</ref> He is a Consulting Editor for the [[Journal of Late Antiquity]] and a Scientific Advisor for ''Revue Antiquité tardive''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://muse.jhu.edu/journal/399 |title=Journal of Late Antiquity |publisher=Project MUSE |date= |accessdate=2016-11-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://antiquite-tardive.com/spip.php?rubrique7&lang=fr |title=Revue Antiquité tardive |publisher=Association pour l’Antiquité tardive |date= |accessdate=2016-11-17}}</ref> From 2006 to 2009 he served on the Council of the [[Society for the Promotion of Hellenic Studies]] and on the council for the [[British Institute at Ankara]] from 2011 to 2015.<ref name=ncl/><ref>{{citation |title=Law and Empire, AD 193–455: The Project Volterra |publisher=Amministrazione di Athenæum, Università |language=Italian |year=2003 |journal=Athenaeum |page=725 |volume=91 |location=no. 2 |issn=0004-6574 |oclc=98047545 |url=http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/98047545}}</ref><ref name=Kaiser2009>{{citation |title=Project Volterra II (Law and the End of the Empire), Colloquium 2: Authorities and Subjects and Manuals and Jurisprudence, London, UC, 15.-16. September 2008 |last=Kaiser |first=Wolfgang |publisher=H. B̐ưohlau |language=German |year=2009 |journal=Zeitschrift der Savigny-Stiftung für Rechtsgeschichte. Romanistische Abtheilung |page=682 |location=126 |issn=0323-4096 |oclc=440690917 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.press.jhu.edu/journals/journal_of_late_antiquity/editorial.html |title=Journal of Late Antiquity |publisher=The Johns Hopkins University Press |accessdate=3 December 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://biaa.ac.uk/ |title=Home |publisher=BIAA |date= |accessdate=2016-11-13}}</ref>
In 2016 Corcoran was a member of the panel for [[BBC Radio 4]]'s [[In Our Time (radio series)|In Our Time]] episode on [[Corpus Juris Civilis|Justinian's Legal Code]] with [[Caroline Humfress]] and [[Paul du Plessis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b082j2q2 | publisher=BBC Radio 4 | date= November 2016 | title = In Our Time: Justinian's Legal Code}} * Extended podcast version: [http://open.live.bbc.co.uk/mediaselector/5/redir/version/2.0/mediaset/audio-nondrm-download/proto/http/vpid/p04gpmjh.mp3 link]</ref>
==Gregorian Code discovery==
In 2010 the Volterra database was used by Corcoran and [[Benet Salway|Salway]] to identify previously unknown fragments of the [[Gregorian Code]]. The "Fragmenta Londiniensia" are seventeen pieces of parchment estimated to date from AD400, the document having been cut up and re-used as book-binding material. This is the first direct evidence yet discovered of the Gregorian Codex.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roger-pearse.com/weblog/?p=3466 |title=Lost Roman legal text found |first=Roger |last=Pearse |date=27 January 2010 |accessdate=27 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.ahrc.ac.uk/News/Podcasts/Pages/lostromanlaw.aspx |title=Lost Roman law code discovered in London |publisher=[[Arts and Humanities Research Council]] |date=28 January 2010 |accessdate=28 January 2010 |format=Podcast |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100314192605/http://www.ahrc.ac.uk/News/Podcasts/Pages/lostromanlaw.aspx |archivedate=14 March 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=Jack2010 >{{cite news |title=Cracking the codex: Long lost Roman legal document discovered |last=Jack |first=Malcolm |date=28 January 2010 |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/science/archaeology/news/cracking-the-codex-long-lost-roman-legal-document-discovered-1881769.html|quote=These fragments are the first direct evidence of the original version of the Gregorian Code. Our preliminary study confirms that it was the pioneer of a long tradition that has extended down into the modern era and it is ultimately from the title of this work, and its companion volume the Codex Hermogenianus, that we use the term ‘code’ in the sense of ‘legal rulings’.}}</ref><ref name=Guardian2010 >{{cite news |title=Experts identify scraps of lost Roman law text: Copy of the Gregorian Code, which was first drafted in AD300, had been chopped up and used to cover medieval book |last=Kennedy |first=Maev |date=28 January 2010 |newspaper=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2010/jan/28/gregorian-text-roman-law-found|quote=The fragments were bought by a private collector at a sale in London. After failing either to translate the script or identify the subject, he circulated photocopies which eventually reached Salway and Corcoran.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Rachel Kaufman |url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2010/02/100203-lost-codex-gregorianus-roman-law-book/ |title=Lost Roman Codex Fragments Found in Book Binding |publisher=National Geographic |date=2010-02-10 |accessdate=4 February 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5uESdkIoR?url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2010/02/100203-lost-codex-gregorianus-roman-law-book/ |archivedate=14 November 2010 |deadurl=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref>
