{{Inline|date=August 2016}}

'''Yahad-In Unum (YIU)''' is a French organization founded to locate the sites of [[mass grave]]s of Jewish victims of the Nazi mobile killing units, especially the ''[[Einsatzgruppen]]'', in [[Ukraine]], [[Belarus]], [[Russia]], [[Poland]] and [[Moldova]]. It was founded in [[Paris]] in 2004 by leaders in the French Roman Catholic and Jewish communities. YIU is led by Father [[Patrick Desbois]], a [[Roman Catholic priest|Catholic priest]] whose grandfather was a French soldier deported to the Nazi [[internment|prison camp]] [[Rava-Ruska]], located in a Ukrainian town that borders [[Poland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://momentmag.com/moment/issues/2011/12/desbois.html|title=A Priest Bears Witness - Moment Magazine|publisher=Momentmag.com|date=7 February 2012|accessdate=5 October 2015}}</ref> Its United States fundraising branch is known as the '''American Friends of Yahad-In Unum'''.

==Leadership==
Father Patrick Desbois is the director of the '''Episcopal Committee for Relations with Judaism'''. His work on Catholic-Jewish relations has frequently received international recognition; he has received the [[Légion d'honneur]] from [[President of the French Republic|French president]], [[Nicolas Sarkozy]], and been awarded the Medal of Valor by the [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]], the Roger E. Joseph Prize by [[Hebrew Union College]], the Humanitarian Award by the [[U.S. Holocaust Memorial Museum]], the [[Jan Karski]] Award by the [[American Jewish Committee]], the [[B'nai B'rith]] International Award for Outstanding Contributions to Relations with the Jewish People and the National Jewish Book Award for his 2008 book ''Holocaust by Bullets'' (Palgrave-Macmillan). 

In 2009, he received [[Honorary degree|honorary doctorates]] from [[Hebrew University]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholic.co.il/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=413%3Afather-patrick-desbois-receives-a-phd-from-hebrew-university&catid=30%3Anews-archives&Itemid=36&lang=en|title=''Holocaust by Bullets''|publisher=Catholic.co.il|accessdate=5 October 2015}}</ref> and [[Bar Ilan]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.biu.ac.il/indexE.php?id=33&pt=20&pid=117&level=2&cPath=33&type=1&news=590|title=Honorary Doctorates Awarded During Bar-Ilan University's 54th Annual Board of Trustees Meetings|publisher=.biu.ac.il|date=12 May 2009|accessdate=5 October 2015}}</ref> 2012 from the [[New York University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyu.edu/about/news-publications/news/2012/03/22/us-supreme-court-justice-sonia-sotomayor-to-speak-at-nyus-2012-commencement-.html|title=US Supreme Court Justice Sonia Sotomayor to Speak at NYU's 2012 Commencement|date=22 March 2012|publisher=Nyu.edu|accessdate=5 October 2015}}</ref>

Dr. [[Richard Prasquier]] is the vice-president of the Yahad-In Unum Board. He is the president of the Representative Council of French Jewish Institutions and a member of the [[World Jewish Congress]] and the International Jewish Committee on Inter-religious Consultations.{{cn|date=August 2016}}

David Black is the president of American Friends of Yahad-In Unum. Black is the associate vice president for Institutional Advancement for [[Yeshiva University]]. He is the former director of the [[Jewish Community Center]] in Manhattan and executive director of the [[Alliance Francaise]] in New York.{{cn|date=August 2016}}

==Historical background==
In less than two years, from June 1941 until the spring of 1943, an estimated 1.25 million Jews were massacred in [[Soviet Union|the Soviet Union]] by Nazi mobile killing units, or ''[[Einsatzgruppen]]''. The ''Einsatzgruppen'' rounded up the Jewish populations of the villages and towns they passed through, led them to the country-side and summarily executed them. The victims were buried (many of them still alive) in mass graves. Very little is known about these atrocities because there were so few survivors.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Einsatzgruppen Reports: Selections from the dispatches of the Nazi Death Squads' campaign against the Jews: July 1941–January 1943|editor=[[Yitzhak Arad]]|editor2=Shmuel Krakowski|editor3=Shmuel Spector|author=Stella Schossberger (translator)|publisher=United States Holocaust Museum|date=1990|isbn=978-0896040571}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Crowe|first=David|title=The Holocaust: Roots, History, and Aftermath|location=Boulder, Colorado|publisher=Westview Press|date=2008|isbn=978-0813343259}}</ref>

==Research==
{{unsourced|section|date=October 2015}}
YIU seeks to find evidence of the massacres on the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern front]] and locate the mass graves of Jews killed by the ''Einsatzgruppen''. YIU's objective is to counter the claims of [[Holocaust deniers]] who use the lack of official documentation of the murders to make claims about the validity of [[Holocaust]] evidence, and to account for the graves that remain undiscovered to pay respect to the dead.

YIU approaches its work on two fronts—archival research and research trips. The archival research is primarily undertaken by [[PhD]] and [[Graduate school|graduate students]] in the [[United States]] and [[Germany]]. The researchers spend several months at the [[United States Holocaust Memorial Museum]], where they study the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] archives of the Extraordinary State Commission of 1944 and the archives from the [[Einsatzgruppen Trial]] at [[Ludwigsburg]], Germany.

After the research is complete, an 11-person team, usually led by [[Patrick Desbois]], travels to Belarus and Ukraine to collect testimonial and [[Forensic identification|forensic evidence]] of the murders. Each trip lasts 15–20 days. The team includes a photographer, ballistics expert, translators, drivers, daily report recorders, a witness interviewer and [[camera operator]]. During each trip, the team travels from village to village, where they interview and film the surviving eyewitnesses, using testimony of witnesses to discover the locations of the graves. Once the graves are located, the team uses high-tech equipment to obtain forensic evidence that validates the testimonies. When the team returns to Paris, the translated video testimony and the [[physical evidence]] is archived.

==Publications==
In August 2008, [[Palgrave MacMillan]] published ''Holocaust By Bullets'', written by Father Desbois about the work of YIU. Father Desbois titled the book after one of the methods the [[Nazism|Nazis]] used to kill their victims. The [[Jewish Book Council]] awarded the book the 2008 [[National Jewish Book Award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishbookcouncil.org/awards/njba-list|title=NJBA Winners|publisher=Jewishbookcouncil.org|accessdate=5 October 2015}}</ref>

In June 2014, YIU published its ten-year anniversary book. Called Broad Daylight, the book encapsulates the horror of the Jewish genocide in which Germans in Eastern Europe massacred the Jews in broad daylight. The bilingual book (written in French and English)covers each territory that the organization has researched, splitting each into a chapter. These include, Ukraine, Belarus, Russia, Poland, Romania, Moldova and Lithuania.{{cn|date=October 2015}}

==Future projects==
YIU continues to work in Ukraine and Belarus and plans to expand to [[Russia]] and [[Poland]]. Since 2009, the ''Archives and Research Center'' (CERRESE - ''Centre Européen de Ressources pour la Recherche et l'Enseignement sur la Shoah à l'Est''), a unique research center in Paris, features unique archival resources and the new results from Father Desbois' [[field research]], including video testimonies and artifacts.<ref>[http://www.yahadinunum.org/index.php/about-yahad/archives-and-research-center-cerrese YIU website] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120702075809/http://www.yahadinunum.org/index.php/about-yahad/archives-and-research-center-cerrese |date=July 2, 2012 }}</ref>

In addition, YIU is planning to bring a special touring exhibit to schools in Ukraine. YIU will also continue the global tour of its educational exhibits, which include trainings and [[public education]] programs. Finally, they plan to host a conference at the [[Sorbonne]] about [[Sonderaktion 1005]], the Nazis' attempts to erase evidence of the mass murder of Jews.{{cn|date=August 2016}}

The organization is also expanding an interactive map on its website, on which users can see the extent to which the Nazis attempted to wipe out the Jewish population in remote villages. The map covers all the countries in which the organization has expanded its research. It enables users to choose a specific country and location and to read information about the testimonies and/or watch a video regarding the town's mass murder.{{cn|date=August 2016}}

